      "id": "intro-header",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "# Part 1: Introduction to Java\n\n## Welcome to Your Java Journey!\n\nThis tutorial series will take you from a complete beginner to being able to build real-world Java applications. By the end, you'll have a solid understanding of Java programming and be able to create your own projects.\n\n---\n\n## What is Java?\n\nJava is one of the most popular programming languages in the world. It was created by James Gosling at Sun Microsystems in 1995.\n\n### Key Features of Java:\n\n1. **Platform Independent** - Write once, run anywhere (WORA). Java code runs on any device with a Java Virtual Machine (JVM)\n2. **Object-Oriented** - Everything in Java is organized around objects and classes\n3. **Simple and Easy to Learn** - Clean syntax similar to English\n4. **Secure** - Built-in security features\n5. **Robust** - Strong memory management and exception handling\n\n### Where is Java Used?\n\n- Android mobile applications\n- Web applications (backend)\n- Enterprise software\n- Desktop applications\n- Scientific applications\n- Big Data technologies\n- Game development",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "intro-header"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "how-java-works",
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": "## How Java Works\n\n```\n+------------------+     +------------------+     +------------------+\n|   Your Code      | --> |    Compiler      | --> |    Bytecode      |\n|   (.java file)   |     |    (javac)       |     |   (.class file)  |\n+------------------+     +------------------+     +------------------+\n                                                          |\n                                                          v\n                                               +------------------+\n                                               |       JVM        |\n                                               | (Java Virtual    |\n                                               |    Machine)      |\n                                               +------------------+\n                                                          |\n                                                          v\n                                               +------------------+\n                                               |   Your Program   |\n                                               |     Runs!        |\n                                               +------------------+\n```\n\n1. You write Java code in a `.java` file\n2. The Java compiler (`javac`) converts it to bytecode (`.class` file)\n3. The JVM reads the bytecode and runs your program\n\nThis is why Java is \"platform independent\" - the JVM is available for Windows, Mac, Linux, etc.",
      "metadata": {
        "language": "markdown",
        "id": "how-java-works"
      }
    },
    {
